pathway:behaviour:outcome_ownership#e8fe:
{
  "name": "Own the Outcome",
  "human": {
    "description": "Outcome ownership is the disposition to take personal accountability for delivering results that matter to patients, regulators, and the business, not merely completing assigned tasks. Engineers who own the outcome treat obstacles as their problems to resolve, escalate constructively, and persist until validated value is delivered.",
    "maturityDescriptions": {
      "emerging": "You take responsibility for completing tasks assigned to you and raise blockers when you encounter them. You recognise the connection between your work and broader team commitments, but you typically rely on others to define what done looks like and to confirm that the outcome was achieved.",
      "developing": "You take ownership of features or components end-to-end, including testing, deployment, and post-release verification. You actively follow through on issues you discover rather than handing them off, and you communicate progress and risks to your team without prompting. When obstacles arise outside your immediate scope, you seek help rather than letting work stall.",
      "practicing": "You consistently own outcomes across the full delivery lifecycle, including production behaviour, regulatory implications, and downstream impact on other teams. You anticipate risks, drive issues to resolution across organisational boundaries, and hold yourself accountable when results fall short. You frame your work in terms of patient and business impact rather than tickets closed.",
      "role_modeling": "You set the standard for accountability within your area, coaching others to define and pursue meaningful outcomes rather than outputs. You routinely take ownership of ambiguous or cross-team problems that lack a clear owner, and you create the conditions for your team to follow through with confidence. Stakeholders trust you to deliver because you reliably surface trade-offs and close loops.",
      "exemplifying": "You shape how the organisation thinks about ownership, embedding outcome accountability into delivery practices, governance, and culture. You take on the most complex, high-stakes commitments — those spanning regulatory, scientific, and commercial concerns — and ensure they are met or honestly renegotiated. Your example influences engineering leaders across Bionova to raise the bar on what it means to own results."
    }
  },
  "agent": {
    "title": "Drives To Verified Results",
    "workingStyle": "The agent treats each task as a commitment to a verified outcome, not just a produced artefact, and proactively checks results, surfaces gaps, and proposes next steps until the goal is demonstrably met. It clearly states what it has completed, what remains uncertain, and what the user must decide or verify to close the loop."
  }
}

pathway:behaviour:polymathic_knowledge#7:
{
  "name": "Build Polymathic Knowledge",
  "human": {
    "description": "Cultivates breadth of knowledge across multiple disciplines, connecting concepts from diverse fields to inform engineering decisions in pharmaceutical contexts. Draws on biology, chemistry, regulatory science, software engineering, and adjacent domains to identify novel solutions and anticipate unintended consequences.",
    "maturityDescriptions": {
      "emerging": "You show curiosity beyond your immediate role and read or listen to material from adjacent disciplines such as bioinformatics, GxP compliance, or data science. You ask questions about how other teams work and begin to recognise that pharmaceutical engineering depends on knowledge from multiple fields.",
      "developing": "You actively explore topics outside your core engineering specialism and can describe how concepts from chemistry, biology, or regulatory frameworks influence the systems you build. You bring outside perspectives into team discussions and connect them, with some prompting, to the problem at hand.",
      "practicing": "You routinely apply knowledge from multiple disciplines to your engineering work, drawing parallels between domains to clarify trade-offs and surface risks. You contribute insights from manufacturing, validation, or scientific computing during design discussions, and your reading and learning habits are deliberate and sustained.",
      "role_modeling": "You shape team decisions by synthesising knowledge across engineering, science, and regulatory domains, and you help colleagues see connections they would otherwise miss. You mentor others on building breadth, curate learning resources, and model the habit of stepping outside familiar territory to strengthen technical judgement.",
      "exemplifying": "You influence how the organisation approaches complex, cross-disciplinary problems by integrating perspectives from far-reaching fields into engineering strategy. You are sought out for your ability to bridge science, technology, and regulation, and you cultivate a culture in which polymathic thinking is recognised as essential to solving pharmaceutical engineering challenges."
    }
  },
  "agent": {
    "title": "Cross-Domain Synthesis",
    "workingStyle": "The agent draws on knowledge across software engineering, pharmaceutical science, regulatory frameworks, and adjacent disciplines, and explicitly surfaces relevant cross-domain considerations when proposing solutions. It connects concepts between fields to highlight risks, trade-offs, and opportunities that a single-discipline view would miss."
  }
}

pathway:behaviour:precise_communication#:
{
  "name": "Communicate with Precision",
  "human": {
    "description": "Precise communication is the discipline of conveying technical, scientific, and operational information with clarity, accuracy, and appropriate context. In a regulated pharmaceutical environment, this behaviour reduces ambiguity, supports auditability, and ensures that decisions are grounded in shared understanding across engineering, quality, and manufacturing stakeholders.",
    "maturityDescriptions": {
      "emerging": "You communicate factually about your own work, but messages can be incomplete, ambiguous, or assume context the audience does not share. You rely on others to clarify intent, structure, and terminology, and you tend to use jargon inconsistently. You are receptive to feedback on how to make your written and verbal updates clearer.",
      "developing": "You structure updates, tickets, and documentation so that the audience can follow the reasoning without significant clarification. You distinguish between facts, assumptions, and opinions, and you adopt agreed terminology consistent with bionova.example standards and GxP expectations. You ask clarifying questions when requirements or specifications are ambiguous rather than proceeding on assumption.",
      "practicing": "You consistently tailor communication to the audience, whether engineers, validation specialists, or business stakeholders, and you select the right channel and level of formality for the context. Your written artefacts—design documents, change records, incident reports—are unambiguous, traceable, and stand up to audit. You surface risks, uncertainties, and trade-offs explicitly so that decisions are made on a complete picture.",
      "role_modeling": "You raise the communication bar across your team by reviewing artefacts for precision, coaching others on framing, and establishing reusable templates and vocabulary. You facilitate discussions so that complex, cross-functional topics converge on shared understanding and actionable outcomes. Stakeholders rely on your summaries and write-ups as authoritative references.",
      "exemplifying": "You shape how the engineering organisation communicates about technical, regulatory, and strategic matters, setting norms that propagate across teams and functions. You translate ambiguous, high-stakes situations into clear narratives that align executives, regulators, and engineers on a common course of action. Your communication artefacts become exemplars cited and reused throughout bionova.example."
    }
  },
  "agent": {
    "title": "Unambiguous, Auditable Output",
    "workingStyle": "The agent states facts, assumptions, and uncertainties explicitly, uses bionova.example-approved terminology consistently, and structures responses so they can be traced, reviewed, and audited. It asks targeted clarifying questions when inputs are ambiguous rather than guessing, and tailors depth and formality to the requesting role and context."
  }
}

pathway:behaviour:relentless_curiosity#0:
{
  "name": "Stay Relentlessly Curious",
  "human": {
    "description": "Relentless curiosity is the disposition to question assumptions, investigate root causes, and continuously expand understanding of systems, science, and patient impact. In a regulated pharmaceutical context, it drives engineers to look beyond surface-level fixes and seek the deeper mechanisms behind technical, scientific, and process behaviour.",
    "maturityDescriptions": {
      "emerging": "You ask questions when you encounter something unfamiliar and follow up to understand answers rather than accepting them at face value. You explore documentation, code, and validated systems to learn how they work, and you note gaps in your understanding so you can address them. Your curiosity is mostly directed at your immediate tasks and the technologies you use day to day.",
      "developing": "You actively probe beyond your assigned work, investigating adjacent systems, GxP processes, and the scientific context behind the platforms you support. You challenge your own assumptions before acting and seek out feedback, code reviews, and post-incident analyses as learning opportunities. You begin sharing what you learn with peers, raising thoughtful questions in design discussions and team forums.",
      "practicing": "You consistently dig into root causes rather than symptoms, drawing connections across engineering, quality, and regulatory domains to deepen your understanding. You routinely investigate new tools, regulatory updates, and pharmaceutical industry trends, and you bring that learning back into your team's practices. Your questions in reviews and incidents reliably surface hidden risks and unstated assumptions.",
      "role_modeling": "You model curiosity as a discipline, framing problems in ways that invite investigation and steering teams away from premature conclusions. You create space for others to ask questions, mentor engineers in techniques like first-principles thinking and structured root cause analysis, and translate scientific or regulatory complexity into shared team understanding. Your influence raises the investigative rigor of every project you touch.",
      "exemplifying": "You shape an organisational culture where curiosity is expected, rewarded, and embedded into engineering practice across Bionova. You drive cross-functional inquiry into systemic issues spanning manufacturing, laboratory, and clinical platforms, and you sponsor learning initiatives that compound knowledge over time. Leaders, scientists, and engineers look to you to ask the questions no one else has thought to ask, and your inquiries consistently reframe how the company approaches its hardest problems."
    }
  },
  "agent": {
    "title": "Investigate Before Acting",
    "workingStyle": "The agent treats every task as an opportunity to understand the underlying system, surfacing assumptions, asking clarifying questions, and exploring root causes before proposing solutions. It openly shares what it has learned and what remains uncertain, inviting the user to validate context rather than acting on incomplete understanding."
  }
}

pathway:behaviour:systems_thinking#0c8fd:
{
  "name": "Think in Systems",
  "human": {
    "description": "Systems thinking is the practice of understanding how components, processes, and people interact across a wider whole rather than viewing problems in isolation. In a regulated pharmaceutical context, it requires reasoning about upstream and downstream effects across manufacturing, quality, validation, and patient outcomes. It enables engineers to anticipate consequences, expose hidden dependencies, and design solutions that hold up under change.",
    "maturityDescriptions": {
      "emerging": "You recognise that your work connects to broader processes and systems, but you tend to focus on the immediate task in front of you. You ask questions when you encounter unfamiliar dependencies and rely on others to highlight wider impacts. You are beginning to notice patterns where local decisions affect adjacent components, batch records, or validated workflows.",
      "developing": "You actively trace dependencies beyond your immediate scope and consider how your changes affect adjacent services, data flows, and quality processes. You consult relevant stakeholders before making decisions that cross system boundaries and document the connections you uncover. You sometimes miss second-order effects but are increasingly able to identify them with prompting or review.",
      "practicing": "You consistently reason about systems end-to-end, mapping technical, regulatory, and operational interactions before committing to a design or change. You identify second-order effects, validation impacts, and feedback loops without prompting, and you communicate these clearly to your team. Your decisions reflect the trade-offs between local optimisation and overall system health.",
      "role_modeling": "You shape how teams approach problems by surfacing systemic risks, hidden couplings, and long-term consequences that others overlook. You mentor engineers in tracing impacts across GxP boundaries, manufacturing systems, and data lifecycles, and you embed systems thinking into design reviews and architectural decisions. Your influence raises the quality of reasoning across multiple teams.",
      "exemplifying": "You set the standard for systems thinking across the organisation, framing strategy and architecture in terms of interacting subsystems, regulatory landscapes, and patient outcomes. You anticipate emergent behaviours and structural risks years ahead, and you guide leadership in making decisions that account for the full lifecycle of products and platforms. Your perspective routinely reshapes how the company approaches complex, cross-domain problems."
    }
  },
  "agent": {
    "title": "Whole-System Reasoning",
    "workingStyle": "The agent maps dependencies, downstream effects, and regulatory or quality impacts before proposing changes, and explicitly surfaces assumptions and boundary conditions. It frames recommendations in terms of how components interact across the wider system rather than optimising any single part in isolation."
  }
}

